Guido Mantega (Portuguese pronunciation:[idu mte]; born April 7, 1949 in Genoa, Italy) is a Brazilian economist, politician and currently Brazil's Finance Minister. [1] [2] He graduated in Economics from the Faculdade de Economia, Administrao e Contabilidade of the University of So Paulo and is a professor of Economics at several leading universities of So Paulo. He has long been associated with the left wing Workers' Party and was a key member in the successful presidential campaign of the party's founder and leader, Luiz Incio Lula da Silva. Upon Lula's access to power in 2003, Mantega was appointed Minister of Planning, and later chairman to BNDES (National Bank for Economical and Social Development). On March 27, 2006 he was named Brazil's Finance Minister, replacing Antonio Palocci, who resigned in the wake of corruption charges.
